Oceasionally, perhaps only once in a decade, in a particu- larly great vintage year, the Counts of Kesselstatt put aside in a special reserve (known as the Schatzkeller or “Treasure Cellar’) a few hundred cases of their most remarkable Moselles. 1949 was such a year. The Moselle vineyards, on the whole, pro- duced wines which, in ele- gance and bouquet, may well prove the best of our genera- tion. Certainly, no finer exam- ples of Moselle can be found than these incomparable wines from the “Treasure Cel- lar.” One of these wines re- ceived the Bundes-Siegerpreis which means that it was ranked as the best 1949 of all Germany. Each bottle of this limited reserve was indi- vidually numbered at the vineyard cellar.
